0],[890,673],[149,673]]},{"text":"population of the towns and cities, limiting the number of people who were","box":[[148,680],[893,679],[893,703],[148,704]]},{"text":"entitled to food rations, welfare and non-agrarian jobs. The leadership of the","box":[[148,709],[890,709],[890,732],[148,732]]},{"text":"CCP hadlearned importantlessons from thefamine.","box":[[148,736],[636,737],[636,760],[148,759]]},{"text":"These measures alone, however, were still inadequate to stabilize the system of","box":[[169,766],[893,766],[893,790],[169,790]]},{"text":"food supply in the post-famine years. Reform had to be coupled with immediate","box":[[148,796],[892,796],[892,819],[148,819]]},{"text":"relief via grain imports. As Chen Yun argued: â€œIf we import grain, we can take","box":[[148,825],[891,825],[891,848],[148,848]]},{"text":"less from the peasants,stabilize their attitude toward production,and raise the","box":[[147,852],[891,853],[891,876],[147,875]]},{"text":"enthusiasm of thepeasantsforproduction.If we take two or threeyearsto","box":[[148,883],[892,883],[892,906],[148,906]]},{"text":"develop agricultural production, the problems of the internal market can be","box":[[149,912],[892,912],[892,935],[149,935]]},{"text":"solved.\"10Between1961and1965,Chinaimportedonaverage5milliontons","box":[[148,939],[894,941],[893,964],[148,962]]},{"text":"of grain each year; net imports stood at around 4.18 million tons per annum.11","box":[[146,966],[894,963],[895,994],[146,997]]},{"text":"Rather than being sent to famine-hit rural areas, this grain was used to supply","box":[[146,997],[888,999],[888,1023],[146,1021]]},{"text":"Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Liaoning. All four areas were part of the urban","box":[[147,1028],[891,1027],[891,1051],[147,1052]]},{"text":"supplysystem administereddirectlybythecentralgovernment,andtheimports","box":[[148,1058],[891,1058],[891,1080],[148,1080]]},{"text":"therefore constituted a kind of indirect famine relief, reducing the burden on","box":[[148,1085],[891,1085],[891,1108],[148,1108]]},{"text":"peasants to meet grain quotas and allowing more grain to remain in the villages.","box":[[145,1117],[890,1116],[890,1140],[145,1141]]},{"text":"9 Yuan Yongxi (ed.),Zhongguo renkou zonglun,p.277.","box":[[156,1182],[592,1183],[592,1206],[156,1205]]},{"text":"I0 Quoted in:Jin Chongji(ed.),Zhou Enlai zhuan(Beijing:Zhongyang wenxian chubanshe,1998),","box":[[147,1204],[892,1205],[892,1228],[147,1227]]},{"text":"Vol.4,p.1565.","box":[[175,1228],[295,1230],[295,1251],[175,1249]]},{"text":"11 LuoPinghan,Da qian xi:1961-1963 nian de chengzhen renkou jing jian (Nanning: Guangxi","box":[[148,1252],[891,1252],[891,1275],[148,1275]]},{"text":"renmin chubanshe,2oo3),p.118.","box":[[175,1275],[433,1277],[433,1297],[175,1294]]},{"text":"Downloaded from https://www.cambridge.org/core. University of Sussex Library, on 29 Apr 2019 at 18:24:26, subject to the Cambridge Core terms of use, available at","box":[[35,1396],[1008,1396],[1008,1415],[35,1415]]},{"text":"https://www.cambridge.org/core/terms.https://doi.org/10.1017/9781316421826.006","box":[[36,1414],[535,1414],[535,1431],[36,1431]]}],"dimensions":{"height":1459,"width":1028}}